'''Grigol Giorgadze''' ({{lang-ka|გრიგოლ გიორგაძე}}) (November 30, 1879&nbsp;– July 18, 1937) was a [[Georgia (country)|Georgian]] historian, jurist and politician.
Born in [[Kutaisi]] into the family of a priest, Giorgadze graduated from a local theological seminary in 1902 and from the [[Kharkiv University]] in 1909. Returning to Georgia, he practiced law in his native Kutaisi from 1909 to 1917. At the same time, he edited the local [[Georgian Social Democratic (Menshevik) Party|Social Democratic Party]] newspaper ''P'oni''. After [[Democratic Republic of Georgia|Georgia]]'s declaration of independence, he served as a [[Ministry of Defense (Georgia)|Minister of War]] in the government of the [[Noe Ramishvili]] from 1918 to 1919 and then was elected to the [[Constituent Assembly of Georgia]]. From 1920 to 1921, he led an opposition group "Skhivi" ("Beam") within the [[Georgian Social Democratic (Menshevik) Party]].<ref>[[Stephen F. Jones]] (2005), ''Socialism in Georgian Colors: The European Road to Social Democracy, 1883-1917'', p. 80. [[Harvard University Press]], {{ISBN|0-674-01902-4}}.</ref> After the [[Red Army invasion of Georgia|Sovietization of Georgia]], he retired from politics and worked as a legal consultant in [[Georgian SSR|Georgia]] and [[Kazakh Soviet Socialist Republic|Kazakhstan]] and engaged in research of pre- and revolutionary Georgia's history. During [[Joseph Stalin]]'s [[Great Purge]], he was arrested, exiled to [[Kazakhstan]], and shot at [[Almaty]].
