'''Muhammad bin Ali Rawandi''' ({{lang-fa|محمدبن علی راوندی}}), was a Persian<ref name="Hillenbrand460">''Muhammad b. Ali Rawandi'', Carole Hillenbrand, '''The Encyclopaedia of Islam''', Vol. VIII, Ed. C.E.Bosworth, E. van Donzel, W.P. Heinrichs and G. Lecomte, (E.J.Brill, 1995), 460.</ref> historian who wrote the ''[[Rahat al-sudur|Rahat al-sudur wa ayat al-surur]]'' during the fall of the [[Great Seljuk Empire]] and the subsequent invasion by the [[Khwārazm-Shāh dynasty|Kharwarzmian empire]].
Rawandi was from a scholarly family and studied [[Hanafi]] fikh in [[Hamadan|Hamadhan]] from 1174 to 1184.<ref name="Hillenbrand460" /> As a calligrapher, Rawandi was brought to court to craft a ''[[Quran]]'' for [[Toghrul III of Seljuq|Toghrul III]] and gained the sultan's favor. After Toghrul's incarceration, Rawandi gained the patronage of Shihab al-Din al-Kashani, who urged him to write the ''Rahat al-sudur''. Rawandi had intended to dedicate his book to [[Süleymanshah II]], but dedicated it to [[Kaykhusraw I]], following the latter's accession as [[Sultanate of Rum|Sultan of Rum]].<ref>''Kaykhusraw'', Claude Cahen, ''The Encyclopaedia of Islam'', Vol. IV, ed. E. Van Donzel, B. Lewis and CH. Pellat, (Brill, 1997), 816.</ref> Later the ''Rahat al-sudur'' was translated into Turkish during the reign of [[Murad II]].
==Modern era== In 1921, the ''Rahat al-sudur'' was published by Muhammad Iqbal.<ref name="Luther15">''The History of the Seljuq Turks: from the Jāmi al-Tawārīkh : an Ilkhanid Adaptation of the Saljuq nama'', Transl. Kenneth Allin Luther, Ed. C.E. Bosworth, (Curzon Press, 2001), 15.</ref> It was recognized by Iqbal, Edward G. Browne and Mirza Muhammad Qazwini as a source in other texts namely, ''Jaml al-tawarikh'', ''Rawdat al-safa'' of Mir Kwand and ''Tarikh-i guzida'' of Hamd Allah al-Mustawfi.<ref name="Luther15" />
